448	          <h2>Task-Based Frameworks and Displacement&ndash;Reinstatement</h2>
449	          <p>In this framework, production requires the completion of a range of tasks, each of which can be allocated to either capital or labor, and the resulting allocation determines the "task content of production".[7][9] Countervailing the displacement effect is the reinstatement effect, which arises when new labor-intensive tasks are created in which labor has a comparative advantage, directly increasing both the labor share and labor demand.[7][10][11] Historical examples abound: in the 19th century, technological developments generated employment for line workers, engineers, machinists, repairmen, conductors, managers, and financiers.[7] The pattern was particularly pronounced in manufacturing, where the displacement effect reduced labor demand at about 1.1 percent per year, or about 30 percent cumulatively.[10][11] The baseline estimate of the elasticity of substitution between capital and labor at the industry level is 0.8, while firm-level elasticities are estimated between 0.4 and 0.7.[10][11] Complementary research by Autor, using U.S. data from 1940 through 2018, estimates that more than 60 percent of employment in 2018 was found in job titles that did not exist in 1940.[12] Between 1947 and 1987, wage bill per capita grew at 2.5 percent per year, largely explained by the productivity effect of 2.4 percent per year, while the displacement effect reduced labor demand at about 0.48 percent per year and the reinstatement effect increased it by 0.47 percent per year, yielding a near balance.[10][11]</p>
450	
451	          <h2>Occupational Exposure and Susceptibility to AI</h2>
452	          <p>One framework proposes evaluating the potential impact of large language models by considering their relevance to the tasks workers perform, estimating that roughly 1.8% of jobs could have over half their tasks affected by LLMs with simple interfaces&mdash;jumping to just over 46% when accounting for complementary software.[13] AI's potential impact extends beyond routine tasks to nonroutine ones such as diagnosing health conditions, programming computers, and tracking flight routes, though some affected occupations are augmented rather than replaced.[14] Across OECD countries, the occupations most exposed to AI tend to be white-collar roles such as IT professionals, business professionals, managers, and science and engineering professionals; occupations requiring manual skills are the least exposed.[15] In Korea, 32.2% of firms reported that AI increased the kinds of skills required and 38.3% reported an increase in the level of skills required, while 95.5% reported no workforce changes at the department level and 56.5% said AI replaced specific tasks rather than eliminating positions.[15]</p>
453	
454	          <h2>Empirical Evidence on Employment and Labor Demand</h2>
455	          <p>In occupations where computer use is high, a one standard deviation increase in AI exposure was associated with 5.7 percentage points higher employment growth.[16] Instrumental variable estimates showed AI increased high-skilled employment by 0.376% and medium-skilled employment by 0.397%, while low-skilled employment declined by 0.003%.[17] One study estimated AI will reduce 90:10 wage inequality but will not affect the top 1%.[18] Research on generative AI's short-term effects in an online labor market found it reduced overall demand for workers.[19] Another analysis observed that AI's impact has been modest so far, echoing past innovation cycles.[21] Jobs for AI and Machine Learning specialists have been rising at a compounding rate of 32% per year between 2016 and 2023.[22]</p>
