469	          <h2>Productivity Effects of Generative AI</h2>
470	          <p>In a preregistered experiment, Noy et al. (2023) assigned writing tasks to 453 professionals and randomly exposed half to ChatGPT, finding average time taken decreased by 40% and output quality rose by 18%, while reducing inequality between workers.[24] A systematic review of 194 peer-reviewed articles (2011&ndash;2025) concludes AI functions as a general-purpose technology with uneven, context-dependent effects.[25] An ILO research brief across seven countries finds productivity gains are real albeit often unverified and uneven, and worker-reported time savings of a few percent have not yet translated into higher measured output, earnings, or employment.[26] Among workers using generative AI at least once in the previous month, 31.9% spent an hour or more per workday using it.[27] Information services showed the largest share of work hours using generative AI at 14.0% and the highest time savings at 2.6%.[27] A standard model estimated self-reported time savings translate to a 1.1% increase in aggregate productivity.[27]</p>
