486	          <h2>Wage Inequality, Skill Demand, and Labor Polarization</h2>
487	          <p>The share of the employed population with AI skills remains small&mdash;at most 0.3% in OECD countries on average&mdash;but is growing rapidly, with nearly half the AI workforce in the top two deciles of the labour earnings distribution.[28] A one standard deviation increase in AI exposure is associated with a 0.4 percentage point increase in wage growth, driven by occupations requiring high software familiarity.[28][29] These patterns imply AI has the potential to exacerbate labor market polarization, as benefits accrue disproportionately to workers already at the upper end of the skill and income distribution.[29][30] Job vacancies for AI roles have increased seven-fold since 2012, and jobs requiring AI skills have grown 3.5 times faster than overall vacancies.[31] Notably, generative AI applications benefit the least experienced workers most, with less experienced programmers completing tasks over 50% faster&mdash;suggesting AI may under certain conditions decrease performance inequality.[28]</p>
488	
489	          <h2>Policy Implications and Frameworks for Managing Disruption</h2>
490	          <p>Sectoral reallocation can be costly because of potential mismatch between the skills of unemployed workers and those required by firms.[34] Cazzaniga and others (2024) assume AI shocks would reduce the labor share by 5.5 percentage points based on the historical UK change between 1980 and 2014.[34] A significantly larger share of employment is in occupations with high augmentation potential across regions, ranging from 10.2 percent in Sub-Saharan Africa to 16.1 percent in Southeastern Asia and the Pacific.[35] Online platform workers in the US regularly report median earnings of roughly $2 to $3 per hour, well below the federal minimum wage.[35]</p>
491	
492	          <h2>Cross-Study Synthesis and Conclusions</h2>
493	          <p>The cross-study evidence reveals a field still in its earliest stages, with convergent acknowledgment that current findings are fragmented and preliminary.[36][37] Early large-scale evidence is consistent with the hypothesis that the AI revolution is beginning to have a significant and disproportionate impact on entry-level workers in the American labor market.[37] Some research found a decline in job postings began in 2022, prior to ChatGPT, corresponding better to rising interest rates than to LLMs, and Frank et al. (2026) found similar results.[36] Important questions about AI's effects on the labor market remain unanswered, and there is a need for more research and better data.[37][36][35]</p>
494	
495	          <h2>Limitations</h2>
496	          <p>The corpus exhibits tier-distribution gaps, with only 6% of sources classified as T1 primary studies and 21% falling into T6, while a further 15% remain UNKNOWN. No contradictions were detected across paired sources, so no cross-source disagreement is asserted. The telemetry block does not surface a date range, limiting characterization of the evidence horizon.</p>
